args: Make it shine, make it shine,\nmake it shiiiiine...
Now THAT'S what I call a sheen.
You seem to be in a good mood, Fritz.\nWhat's going on?
Oh, I'm just polishing my daggers.\nGotta keep your partners happy!
The weather's great, my daggers are nice\nand sharp... That's enough to make a man\nwanna sing, don't you think?
I suppose so. Mind if I take a look\nat your partners there?
Wow, you really do take\ngood care of these.
They're basically my life—they've sure\nsaved it plenty of times.
I imagine your skill with these daggers is\nreflected in that meticulous care.
I was always told that a first-rate warrior\ntakes good care of their weapon.
Couldn't agree more. Keeping your stuff\nin good order is part of being a pro.
There's nothing more sad than blaming\nyour tools when you mess up.
I guess that makes you the pro's pro\nwhen it comes to dagger-wielding?
Hey, if you don't treat that like a joke,\nI'm gonna sound like a real blowhard.
There's nothing arrogant about speaking\nthe truth. You should be proud.
I've had the pleasure of seeing you throw\ndaggers in a variety of situations...
And I've never seen you miss.\nNot even once.
I see what you're saying,\nbut it's not amazing at all.
If I was an ordinary performer like the rest\nof the troupe, I might agree—but I'm not.
My skills are nothing to be praised.
I learned all my dagger-throwing skills\nfrom my time as a thief.
When your life is all about breaking in and\nnot being caught, you either learn those\nskills fast or die before you can.
Someone's knife has to hit first,\nafter all.
That perfect accuracy of mine is\nsomething I learned out of necessity.
So do you get what I'm saying now?\nThere's nothing to praise or admire in\nthings you learn for your own survival.
Maybe that was how you used your skills\nbefore, but you don't do so anymore.\nThat has to count for something.
Heh. Thanks for sticking up for me.\n...Kinda funny how this old life ends\nup rolling around, isn't it?
The skills I used to hurt people are now\nbeing used to make them happy.
I'm just a fool whose entire life\nis one big contradiction.
If that's how you feel, why are you still\nusing daggers in your performances?
Something must keep you going if you feel\nthat strongly about your past.
I do it because it's what I wanted.
After all the time I spent living in the\nshadows, the circus felt...dazzling.
I still remember the first day I saw it.\nI was on the run from some guards,\nand ended up hiding in the troupe's tent.
Annelie knew nothing about me, but she\nlet me stay and watch the show anyway.
That sounds just like her. I take it that's\nwhat made you decide to join up?
That's right. She's really amazing.\nHeck, she took my cares away while\nI was running from a bunch of guards!
Her actions were enough to make\neven a fool like me want to bring\nthat same joy to others.
But no matter how many people I make\nhappy, I'm still tossing these daggers for\nmyself at the end of the day.
So that's why I keep saying there's\nnothing amazing about it.
Look, maybe you learned those skills for\nyour own selfish reasons, but you're still\nusing them for good things now.
Your skills captivate hearts and bring\nsmiles to even the gloomiest faces.
And that's a pretty amazing thing.
Something that benefits others doesn't\nbecome a bad thing just because you're\nalso doing it for yourself, right?
If anything, making yourself AND others\nhappy is the best possible outcome.
So yeah, I still think you're amazing—\nand nothing you say will change that.
Still, guys like me just can't hope to\ncompare to someone who lives an\nhonest life from cradle to casket.
I don't think that's true. I mean, you always\nsay you never miss anything you set your\neyes on, right?
So why would your own LIFE be the\none exception to that rule?
I guess I'll need to keep pursuing this\ndream for a while longer, huh?
Just you wait. I'll get the life I want,\nand you'll be there to witness it.
